GitOps — Run Kubernetes at scale elegantly

Newton Costa

Just now·8 min read

In a dynamic and agile environment, application and infrastructure grows rapidly, and keeping track of all changes and manage the whole cloud stack can be a very tough journey.

So that’s way GitOps comes to play, bringing news perspective in a way we usually manage cloud-native application and run Kubernetes in production and at scale, so let’s dive in.

First thing first, It’s known that modern software development practices focus on some main activities such as:

  1. Source code management using tools like Git
  2. Automated building and testing of applications using CI tools like CodeBuild, Jenkins
  3. Automated deployment using tools like CodeDeploy

Taking the idea of automation to the next level, the standard CI/CD pipeline often combines these activities, where the build service watches the git repo and automatically triggers a build in response to changes in the source code. The practice of Continous Deployments extends the CI pipeline, by automatically deploying the new changes after it has successfully passed through the build and test stages.

What’s GitOps?

“GitOps is a fast-growing ‘operating model’ that combines modern and tested practices for deploying and managing cloud native infrastructure and applications commonly associated with Kubernetes.”

GitOps upholds and iterates on ideas drawn from DevOps and Site Reliabiliy Engineering, using Git everywhere as a single source of truth, bringing the deployment and the ops experience closer to the developers enhancing that experience when running applications on Kubernetes clusters or cloud native.

GitOps requires the desired state of the system to be stored in version control such that anyone can view the entire audit trail of changes. All changes to the desired state are fully traceable commits associated with committer information, commit IDs and time stamps. This means that both the application and the infrastructure are now versioned artefacts and can be audited using the gold standards of software development and delivery.

GitOps Journey

  1. On August 7th, 2017 the term GitOps was introduced by Alexis Richardson of Weaveworks in the “Operations by Pull Request” blog
  2. Since the blog post, GitOps has grown seeing a buzz in the community online and places like Kubecon
  3. There have been many tools developed to support GitOps, numerous talks, articles, blogs, and several books on the way about it
  4. December 10th, 2020 the GitOps Working Group hosted its first meeting as a step towards governance, documentation, guidelines and a clear definition for GitOps

GitOps can be summarized as these two aspects:

  1. An operating model for Kubernetes and other cloud native technologies, providing a set of best practices that unify deployment, management and monitoring for containerized clusters and applications.
  2. A path towards a developer experience for managing applications; where end-to-end CI/CD pipelines and Git workflows are applied to both operations, and development.

Key Principles of GitOps

  1. The entire system described declaratively

Declarative means that configuration is guaranteed by a set of facts instead of by a set of instructions. With your application’s declarations versioned in Git, you have a single source of truth. Your apps can then be easily deployed and rolled back to and from Kubernetes.

2. The canonical desired system state versioned in Git.

You have a single place from which everything is derived and driven when the declaration of your system stored in a version control system and serving as your canonical source of truth.

3. Approved changes that can be automatically applied to the system.

In GitOps, changes are applied using a ‘pull’ model. A GitOps tools continually polls Git repositories looking for changes. When a change is detected, it automatically ‘pulls’ the change and deploys it to a target location.

4. Software agents to ensure correctness and alert on divergence

Once the state of your system is declared and kept under version control, software agents can inform you whenever reality doesn’t match your expectations. The use of agents also ensures that your entire system is self-healing (no just when nodes/pods fail, but in a broader sense human error.) See GitOps An operating Model for Cloud Native

Learn more about these principles in the newly formed GitOps Working Group.

Understanding the GitOps Workflow

There are two types of changes to a software system — feature changes, and configuration changes. Feature changes are packaged and deployed in a container, while configuration changes are defined in YAML files in Kubernetes. These changes are made by two different teams (Dev and Ops) and can be contained to the following two main activities:

  • Updates to container images
  • Updates to the declarative specification, or in other words, the desired state

Typical workflow for creating or updating a new feature:

  1. A pull request for a new feature is pushed to GitHub for review.
  2. The code is reviewed and approved by a colleague. After the code is revised, and re-approved it is merged to Git.
  3. The Git merge triggers the CI and build pipeline, runs a series of tests and then eventually builds a new image and deposits to the new image to a registry.
  4. The ‘Operator’ (installed to the cluster) watches the image registry, notices the image, pulls the new image from the registry and updates its YAML in the config repo.
  5. The ‘Operator’, detects the ‘drift’ (difference between the current state and the desired state of the system). It pulls the changed manifests from the config repo and deploys the new feature to production.

Changes are made via pull requests

GitOps uses a pull strategy that consists of two key components: a “Git repository” as single source of truth for app and manifest (or a config repo) and “Operator” as deployment automaton or synchronizer.

As we saw on the typical workflow, Developers push their updated code to the code base repository; where the change is picked up by the CI tool and ultimately builds a Docker image. The ‘operator’ notices the image, pulls the new image from the repository and then updates its YAML in the config repo. The “operator”, then detects that the cluster is out of date, and it pulls the changed manifests from the config repo and deploys the new image to the cluster.

GitOps Tooling and Kubernetes Ecosystem

Some may think that if they use Kubernetes and GitHub they’re already practicing GitOps. However, this is not true. What’s required is a dedicated GitOps tools that can help drive state to the correct state based on how the system is declared in configuration.

GitOps Operators, It takes over the role of the pipeline by continuously comparing the desired state in the environment repository with the actual state in the deployed infrastructure. Many options has coming as far as GitOps has been adopted. Gitops operators comes typically in two category:

Infrastructure automation operators: Kubestack and JenkinsX, to deal with things such as:

  • Terraform for setup/upgrade/modify
  • Cloud IaaS, IAM, Kubernetes, Cluster, Namespaces, Ingress Controller, Service Mesh, Monitoring

Application automation operators: Flux, Argo CD, both comes to automate application deployment, dealing with:

  • K8s manifest
  • Deployment, Pods, Services, ConfigMaps, Namespaces etc

See CNCF continuous integration radar about GitOps operators

Container Registry, there is many options out there for host container images, such as Helm Registry, Azure Container Registry .

Runtime Environment, think runtime as your cloud infrastructure or your Kubernetes cluster (ie K8s cluster with multiple namespaces or 1 K8s cluster per environment).

Benefits of GitOps

The benefits of applying GitOps best practices are far reaching and provide:

  • Complete platform: Single platform for infrastructure, core components and applications.
  • Increased Productivity: Dramatically increase deployments and faster feedback and control loop
  • High Reliability: Enables cluster and application operator model with standardised tooling
  • Compliance and Security: Enforces standard security policy and an audit trail
  • Multi-cloud and on-premise: Deploy a complete cluster from git with all applications

Few tips to Onboarding GitOps

With this background, maybe you wondering Is my project is ready for GitOps? The answer is: Most Likely! The cool thing about GitOps is that you don’t need to write any code differently. All you need to get started is infrastructure that can be managed with declarative Infrastructure as Code tools.

  1. Select an application: This can be an existing application, or you can go ahead and start with a greenfield application and then pick others application as time goes on. It’s critical that you star with an application instead of multiple don’t try to boil the ocean on your first trip out with GitOps.
  2. Decide on runtime environment structure: Runtime environment is basically your production environment, design how your infrastructure will be, maybe running Kubernetes Cluster maintained by your own, maybe pick a new Cloud Provider that serve Kubernetes cluster, decide what Container Registry to host your image, select your secret provider (like HashiCorp Vault or a cloud provider vault), things like backup strategy, monitoring tool to use (like Prometheus), so you need just sit down and map out and decide all this things.
  3. Decide tooling for deploying runtime infrastructure: As we saw above, there’re some tools doing good job around GitOps, just decide what tool most support your needs, tools like Jenkins X, Kubestack, Terraform , these has been the first choices.
  4. Select source control and Setup Git repos: Most organizations will already have a source control selected, and then you just need to go ahead and set up the Git repos, design how many repos you’re going to have, what level of separation you’re planning to have there. You ma pick source control tools like Azure DevOps, GitHub, Bitbucket, GitLab, and the list goes on.
  5. Select Operator and Sync method: Without operator you don’t have GitOps, so you need decide what operator to use and then decide on a sync method. Many options tools has coming, as we mention before It could be Flux, ArgoCD, Jenkins X
